WEBVTT

00:00:32.806 --> 00:00:34.801
(HEART BEATING STEADILY)

00:00:54.290 --> 00:00:56.493
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING)

00:01:02.967 --> 00:01:04.171
(GROANS SOFTLY)

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:26.325
(EXHALES)

00:01:31.766 --> 00:01:33.266
That was a long one.

00:01:37.668 --> 00:01:42.272
I don't suppose you can tell me
how it looks, can you?

00:01:42.307 --> 00:01:45.375
Unfortunately,
I'm just the technician.

00:01:45.411 --> 00:01:47.841
Your doctor will have
your results tomorrow.

00:01:49.482 --> 00:01:51.647
-Would you like some help to...
-Thank you very much.

00:01:52.588 --> 00:01:53.682
You're very kind.

00:02:02.863 --> 00:02:04.657
CHRIS: I mean, yeah,

00:02:04.692 --> 00:02:08.001
the cancer has brought
grief and pain

00:02:08.036 --> 00:02:11.304
and fear into my every
waking moment.

00:02:12.272 --> 00:02:16.603
GROUP LEADER: Okay, Chris.
Today is a gift.

00:02:16.638 --> 00:02:19.877
That's why they call it
the present.

00:02:19.913 --> 00:02:20.940
(JOHN SIGHS SOFTLY)

00:02:22.012 --> 00:02:23.110
Anyone else?

00:02:23.146 --> 00:02:24.848
(SIGHS WEARILY)

00:02:24.884 --> 00:02:26.585
Henry Kessler.

00:02:26.620 --> 00:02:28.051
Please.

00:02:28.086 --> 00:02:30.719
Stage four pancreatic.

00:02:31.219 --> 00:02:32.424
Terminal.

00:02:33.293 --> 00:02:36.593
That's what they tell me,
anyway, but...

00:02:39.562 --> 00:02:41.631
I'm gonna fight this
'til the end.

00:02:45.972 --> 00:02:47.703
How much time do I have?

00:02:51.205 --> 00:02:52.477
A year?

00:02:53.275 --> 00:02:56.216
Months at best.

00:02:56.252 --> 00:02:59.486
I still have a lot of work
that needs to be done.

00:02:59.522 --> 00:03:00.551
My advice?

00:03:02.051 --> 00:03:03.085
Retire.

00:03:03.120 --> 00:03:04.357
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

00:03:05.222 --> 00:03:07.291
You know, at this stage,

00:03:07.326 --> 00:03:09.855
everyone always searches
for a way out.

00:03:09.890 --> 00:03:13.931
But sometimes,
those who accept their fate,

00:03:13.967 --> 00:03:15.064
have an easier time.

00:03:15.099 --> 00:03:16.732
Easier time? What?

00:03:18.133 --> 00:03:19.438
Dying?

00:03:21.769 --> 00:03:26.676
So, your advice to me
is to die easy?

00:03:32.380 --> 00:03:33.412
(MONITOR BEEPING)

00:03:33.448 --> 00:03:34.481
(VENTILATOR HISSING)

00:03:34.516 --> 00:03:36.719
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING)

00:04:32.273 --> 00:04:33.809
(GASPS)

00:04:39.721 --> 00:04:41.317
(PANTING)

00:04:41.352 --> 00:04:44.754
Help! Hey! Help! Help, please!

00:04:46.895 --> 00:04:48.626
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

00:04:54.369 --> 00:04:57.262
JIGSAW: (OVER SPEAKER)
I'd like to play a game.

00:04:57.298 --> 00:05:01.606
Perhaps one that addresses
those sticky fingers of yours.

00:05:02.940 --> 00:05:07.810
I've had my eyes on you
and I do not like what I see.

00:05:09.218 --> 00:05:12.450
Your job as a custodian
is a noble one.

00:05:12.486 --> 00:05:15.250
Sanitizing and sterilizing
the hospital...

00:05:15.286 --> 00:05:16.420
(JANITOR WHIMPERING)

00:05:16.456 --> 00:05:18.521
...helping patients
avoid sickness.

00:05:18.557 --> 00:05:20.455
But there is
a sickness inside you

00:05:20.490 --> 00:05:22.090
that needs to be excised.

00:05:22.126 --> 00:05:23.361
(COUGHING)

00:05:23.397 --> 00:05:25.692
You have the ability
to not only save

00:05:25.728 --> 00:05:28.228
your soul today,
but your sight.

00:05:28.264 --> 00:05:29.698
(PANTING)

00:05:29.733 --> 00:05:32.137
All you have to do is
click the dial

00:05:32.172 --> 00:05:34.207
across the five positions

00:05:34.243 --> 00:05:37.207
and you will live to see
another day.

00:05:37.242 --> 00:05:39.372
You have 60 seconds.

00:05:39.408 --> 00:05:40.612
Help, please!

00:05:43.015 --> 00:05:45.045
(WHIMPERING)

00:05:46.585 --> 00:05:49.489
Help me! Please, please,
please. Help. Help!

00:05:50.087 --> 00:05:51.123
(BEEPS)

00:05:51.158 --> 00:05:53.924
-(BONE CRACKS)
-(SCREAMS)

00:05:53.960 --> 00:05:55.321
(TICKING)

00:05:55.357 --> 00:05:57.662
(GRUNTING)

00:06:02.198 --> 00:06:03.234
(BEEPS)

00:06:03.269 --> 00:06:05.571
-(BONE CRACKS)
-(SCREAMS)

00:06:09.176 --> 00:06:11.537
I can't! I can't, I can't!

00:06:11.573 --> 00:06:13.810
(CRYING) Please, no!

00:06:14.783 --> 00:06:15.878
(SCREAMING)

00:06:17.917 --> 00:06:19.013
(BEEPS)

00:06:20.019 --> 00:06:21.884
(SCREAMING)

00:06:24.826 --> 00:06:26.427
Fuck you!

00:06:29.097 --> 00:06:30.523
-(ALARM BUZZING)
-(SCREAMING)

00:06:30.558 --> 00:06:32.697
(MACHINE WHIRRING)

00:06:44.980 --> 00:06:46.339
(MACHINE WINDS DOWN)

00:06:46.374 --> 00:06:48.207
(CRYING)

00:06:50.413 --> 00:06:52.453
(CRYING ECHOES)

00:06:53.119 --> 00:06:55.082
(MONITOR BEEPING)

00:07:09.068 --> 00:07:10.471
Good choice.

00:07:14.471 --> 00:07:16.675
(SOMBER MUSIC PLAYING)

00:07:31.126 --> 00:07:32.891
BARISTA: Here you go, sir.

00:07:32.927 --> 00:07:33.956
Thank you.

00:07:47.772 --> 00:07:50.610
HENRY: Can I get
a blueberry scone, please?

00:07:52.674 --> 00:07:54.207
Oh, they look good.

00:07:56.016 --> 00:07:57.012
Thank you.

00:08:01.317 --> 00:08:02.523
Henry.

00:08:04.190 --> 00:08:05.392
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

00:08:05.427 --> 00:08:08.092
We were in the same
cancer support group.

00:08:08.127 --> 00:08:10.094
John Kramer.

00:08:10.130 --> 00:08:11.725
I remember you.

00:08:11.760 --> 00:08:13.864
(CHUCKLES) Hey, good to see you.

00:08:15.201 --> 00:08:16.229
And you as well.

00:08:19.074 --> 00:08:20.307
You look marvelous.

00:08:20.342 --> 00:08:23.003
Thank you. I... I...
I feel great.

00:08:23.038 --> 00:08:25.739
Correct me if I'm wrong,
but you were, uh...

00:08:25.774 --> 00:08:28.280
Yeah, stage four pancreatic.

00:08:28.315 --> 00:08:30.413
But now, four months later,

00:08:30.449 --> 00:08:33.818
I'm in complete remission.

00:08:35.254 --> 00:08:36.722
(BOTH CHUCKLE)

00:08:37.353 --> 00:08:38.559
How?

00:08:39.755 --> 00:08:43.396
It's a... it's a long story.

00:08:43.432 --> 00:08:46.595
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)
I'd love to hear it.

00:08:46.630 --> 00:08:48.129
You got a minute to tell me?

00:08:49.069 --> 00:08:50.835
Sure. Sure.

00:08:56.570 --> 00:08:57.807
So, um,

00:08:57.843 --> 00:09:01.608
I read about a doctor,
a specialist of sorts.

00:09:01.644 --> 00:09:04.084
A Dr. Finn Pederson.

00:09:04.119 --> 00:09:06.680
He offered a treatment

00:09:06.716 --> 00:09:11.523
and it is a groundbreaking

00:09:11.558 --> 00:09:14.694
drug cocktail
combined with surgery.

00:09:20.332 --> 00:09:21.833
It's my war wound.

00:09:24.469 --> 00:09:26.800
I know it looks bad,

00:09:26.835 --> 00:09:30.243
but it was totally worth it.

00:09:30.278 --> 00:09:33.240
-(EXHALES) Yeah.
-(CHUCKLES)

00:09:34.711 --> 00:09:37.915
-Is it available here?
-No.

00:09:37.950 --> 00:09:40.686
No, no, the treatment's not
available in the States.

00:09:40.722 --> 00:09:43.822
The, uh, the medication
isn't approved by the FDA.

00:09:44.822 --> 00:09:47.188
Hell, it isn't approved
by anybody.

00:09:48.496 --> 00:09:51.159
I, um... I haven't
seen them since...

00:09:51.926 --> 00:09:53.997
since my treatment in Norway.

00:09:54.870 --> 00:09:55.867
But...

00:10:01.141 --> 00:10:03.303
this link...

00:10:06.015 --> 00:10:07.010
is still good.

00:10:12.614 --> 00:10:13.819
Hey, John,

00:10:15.817 --> 00:10:18.324
good luck, man. Okay?

00:10:18.359 --> 00:10:20.892
I'm... I'm rooting for you.

00:10:22.129 --> 00:10:23.424
Thank you.

00:10:23.460 --> 00:10:24.665
Take care.

00:10:33.305 --> 00:10:35.368
(JOHN SIGHS)

00:10:42.517 --> 00:10:44.347
Doctor, what exactly is
the procedure?

00:10:44.382 --> 00:10:48.085
Well, under the right
circumstances and with
the proper stimuli,

00:10:48.120 --> 00:10:50.922
genes can be turned on and
turned off like a light switch.

00:10:50.957 --> 00:10:53.226
TV HOST: And you're targeting
the cancer cells?

00:10:53.261 --> 00:10:54.820
FINN PEDERSON: Exactly.

00:10:54.855 --> 00:10:58.428
What we've managed to do is
to create a new cutting-edge
drug cocktail,

00:10:58.464 --> 00:10:59.764
along with surgery,

00:10:59.799 --> 00:11:02.400
to teach the malignant cells
to switch off.

00:11:02.435 --> 00:11:03.902
TV HOST: Fascinating.

00:11:04.402 --> 00:11:05.398
JOHN: Hmm.

00:11:06.307 --> 00:11:07.741
(KEYBOARD CLACKING)

00:11:17.116 --> 00:11:21.351
My father, Dr. Finn Pederson,
was forced into hiding

00:11:21.386 --> 00:11:26.189
by corrupt governments
and their relationship
to big pharma.

00:11:26.225 --> 00:11:28.094
Why?

00:11:28.129 --> 00:11:32.259
Because my father was
on the cusp of curing
dozens of diseases.

00:11:32.295 --> 00:11:36.634
Which means no more need
for lifelong medication.

00:11:36.670 --> 00:11:39.333
Can you imagine
what that implies?

00:11:41.269 --> 00:11:44.041
Well, the big drug companies
certainly can.

00:11:44.076 --> 00:11:48.381
And I'm here to say
that this just cannot stand.

00:11:48.416 --> 00:11:52.882
So, while my father
continues to make further
improvements to his formula,

00:11:52.918 --> 00:11:55.815
I'm taking his treatment
on the road

00:11:55.850 --> 00:11:57.118
for more trials,

00:11:57.153 --> 00:12:00.893
to save as many lives
as humanly possible.

00:12:15.574 --> 00:12:17.338
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

00:12:21.776 --> 00:12:23.311
(EXHALES)

00:12:33.425 --> 00:12:34.795
Who is this?

00:12:35.727 --> 00:12:37.692
This is Cecilia Pederson.

00:12:37.728 --> 00:12:39.195
Is this John Kramer?

00:12:40.135 --> 00:12:41.399
Yes, it is.

00:12:41.434 --> 00:12:43.036
CECILIA: Good.

00:12:43.071 --> 00:12:46.065
We received the email
with your medical records,
Mr. Kramer.

00:12:46.100 --> 00:12:47.667
Thank you for reaching out.

00:12:47.702 --> 00:12:51.278
I'm sifting through
potential candidates
for our program.

00:12:51.313 --> 00:12:52.772
So, I'm calling you now,

00:12:52.808 --> 00:12:55.475
because we have spots opening
for treatment in about
three months.

00:12:56.746 --> 00:12:58.181
(SIGHS WEARILY)

00:13:00.815 --> 00:13:02.251
Mr. Kramer?

00:13:02.785 --> 00:13:04.187
Uh, yes, I'm here.

00:13:05.594 --> 00:13:07.586
You don't have three months,
do you?

00:13:09.726 --> 00:13:11.596
Okay, listen...

00:13:11.631 --> 00:13:13.666
I'm currently working in Mexico.

00:13:13.701 --> 00:13:16.394
Oslo has become
too difficult for us.

00:13:16.430 --> 00:13:18.463
But we have a team
of specialists here

00:13:18.498 --> 00:13:21.368
who share our belief
in the Pederson method

00:13:21.403 --> 00:13:24.005
and I've gathered
a group of eligible patients

00:13:24.041 --> 00:13:26.305
to start treatment
a week from now.

00:13:26.341 --> 00:13:28.409
I think I could add
one more spot.

00:13:29.010 --> 00:13:30.851
If you're interested.

00:13:31.650 --> 00:13:33.018
Yes, I'm interested.

00:13:33.816 --> 00:13:34.915
Henry Kessler...

00:13:34.950 --> 00:13:36.150
referred me to you.

00:13:36.185 --> 00:13:40.454
Henry. He's doing well.
I'm so pleased.

00:13:41.363 --> 00:13:42.489
I wonder if you could...

00:13:42.524 --> 00:13:44.924
could you tell me a little more
about the treatment?

00:13:44.960 --> 00:13:46.728
CECILIA: Of course.

00:13:46.763 --> 00:13:50.602
It's a two-prong treatment
that uses my father's
Xaxiophenol cocktail.

00:13:50.637 --> 00:13:56.405
And in your case, it would be
combined with a cranial surgery
to clear the tumor.

00:13:56.440 --> 00:13:59.544
When both are used together,
the results have been stunning.

00:13:59.579 --> 00:14:01.810
Over 90% success rate.

00:14:01.845 --> 00:14:03.046
I know it's a long trip,

00:14:03.081 --> 00:14:06.482
Mr. Kramer,
especially in your condition,

00:14:06.517 --> 00:14:09.920
but I want you to know
that we found a very
beautiful location

00:14:09.955 --> 00:14:12.592
for our clinic
outside Mexico City.

00:14:12.628 --> 00:14:14.258
It's in a
well-off-the-grid area,

00:14:14.294 --> 00:14:18.056
in the countryside
where you can have
safety and privacy.

00:14:18.092 --> 00:14:22.535
We'll also, of course,
arrange for a trusted
driver at your arrival.

00:14:22.570 --> 00:14:24.130
What date did you have in mind?

00:14:24.165 --> 00:14:27.066
The 5th, Friday after next.

00:14:27.102 --> 00:14:29.107
I think I could make that.

00:14:30.204 --> 00:14:32.407
(MELANCHOLY MUSIC PLAYING)

00:14:40.619 --> 00:14:41.647
(CAR HONKING)

00:14:46.089 --> 00:14:48.220
-J. Kramer? Yeah?
-Si. Yes.

00:14:48.255 --> 00:14:50.959
I'm Diego. Welcome to Mexico.

00:14:50.994 --> 00:14:53.566
Allow me, sir. Please. This way.

00:14:53.602 --> 00:14:56.332
-(JOHN COUGHS)
-There you go.

00:15:00.201 --> 00:15:01.707
DIEGO: Take a look at that.

00:15:01.743 --> 00:15:04.039
That's the Metropolitan
Cathedral.

00:15:04.075 --> 00:15:06.942
That's the revolutionary
memorial.

00:15:06.978 --> 00:15:09.343
That's the Angel
of Independence.

00:15:09.378 --> 00:15:12.480
Take a look at that.
Isn't it beautiful?

00:15:14.453 --> 00:15:15.615
Hey, J.

00:15:15.650 --> 00:15:20.119
That, my friend, that's the old
Aztec statue of Tlaloc.

00:15:20.154 --> 00:15:21.354
That's where the priests

00:15:21.389 --> 00:15:23.255
chop the hearts
out of their subjects

00:15:23.290 --> 00:15:24.924
and roll them down the stairs.

00:15:24.960 --> 00:15:26.559
(DIEGO CHUCKLES)

00:15:26.595 --> 00:15:29.566
Every day, a tourist wants me
to take them here.

00:15:29.602 --> 00:15:31.136
Very strange.

00:15:50.390 --> 00:15:51.620
Hey, J.

00:15:51.656 --> 00:15:52.652
You okay?

00:15:57.063 --> 00:15:59.197
(MEN YELLING INDISTINCTLY
IN SPANISH)

00:16:01.195 --> 00:16:02.560
(IN ENGLISH) Get out!

00:16:02.596 --> 00:16:06.138
(MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY
IN SPANISH)

00:16:08.907 --> 00:16:10.208
(IN ENGLISH) What's your name?

00:16:10.774 --> 00:16:12.211
John Kramer.

00:16:12.246 --> 00:16:15.815
Lie to me again and I'll empty
this chamber in your eye.

00:16:15.850 --> 00:16:18.249
I'm not lying.
My name is John Kramer.

00:16:20.515 --> 00:16:23.218
Not to worry, senor
Kramer, you're fine.

00:16:23.254 --> 00:16:26.692
You're safe. Come with me.
Come, come.

00:16:26.727 --> 00:16:29.689
Here. Welcome. Watch your head.

00:16:53.752 --> 00:16:54.747
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

00:16:55.656 --> 00:16:57.049
(IN ENGLISH) Your room.

00:16:57.084 --> 00:16:58.619
Here. Come.

00:17:00.154 --> 00:17:01.627
(KNOCKING AT DOOR)

00:17:01.662 --> 00:17:03.393
It's here. Good luck.

00:17:10.305 --> 00:17:11.302
Si?

00:17:13.268 --> 00:17:15.768
(IN ENGLISH) I am John Kramer.

00:17:16.872 --> 00:17:18.078
Come.

00:17:18.876 --> 00:17:20.080
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

00:17:28.382 --> 00:17:30.288
(IN ENGLISH) I... Gabriela.

00:17:38.060 --> 00:17:39.429
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

00:17:40.832 --> 00:17:42.333
Mi familia.

00:17:46.706 --> 00:17:47.701
(IN ENGLISH) Come.

00:17:49.071 --> 00:17:50.473
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

00:17:56.014 --> 00:17:57.881
(IN ENGLISH) Sleep. Sleep here.

00:17:57.916 --> 00:18:00.120
Dr. Cecilia Pederson?

00:18:00.784 --> 00:18:01.814
Ah. Si.

00:18:03.254 --> 00:18:07.457
(IN ENGLISH)
She saved life. My life.

00:18:10.257 --> 00:18:12.363
I get. I get now.

00:18:26.208 --> 00:18:28.841
Mr. Kramer, welcome.

00:18:32.620 --> 00:18:34.485
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

00:18:34.520 --> 00:18:38.955
That was quite a reception
that I got on the way out here.

00:18:38.990 --> 00:18:40.622
Oh, our welcome wagon?

00:18:41.662 --> 00:18:43.328
I know, I'm sorry.

00:18:43.363 --> 00:18:46.858
But we've had to beef up
the security wherever we go.

00:18:46.894 --> 00:18:49.830
The big drug companies
are always one step behind

00:18:49.866 --> 00:18:54.207
and so we must keep our location
secret from everyone, even you.

00:18:55.740 --> 00:18:56.776
Come.

00:18:56.811 --> 00:18:58.673
I want you to meet the team.

00:19:07.122 --> 00:19:09.222
-(MAN SPEAKING SPANISH)
-BOY: (IN ENGLISH) Yeah?

00:19:10.189 --> 00:19:14.255
That's Carlos.
Our local football star.

00:19:14.290 --> 00:19:16.427
His father is the caretaker.

00:19:18.897 --> 00:19:20.299
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

00:19:24.364 --> 00:19:26.371
(CARLOS GRUNTING)

00:19:28.171 --> 00:19:30.540
(FOOTBALL THUDDING)

00:19:39.245 --> 00:19:42.720
(IN ENGLISH) This used to be
a chemical factory
back in the day.

00:19:42.756 --> 00:19:44.752
(WATER DRIPPING)

00:19:48.159 --> 00:19:50.362
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING)

00:20:19.155 --> 00:20:20.590
CECILIA: Mateo.

00:20:21.157 --> 00:20:22.895
Hello, Doctor.

00:20:22.930 --> 00:20:24.464
CECILIA: This is John Kramer.

00:20:24.499 --> 00:20:26.691
Very nice to meet you,
Mr. Kramer, and welcome
to our clinic.

00:20:26.727 --> 00:20:28.730
You're in very good hands
with us.

00:20:29.537 --> 00:20:30.666
Hmm.

00:20:30.701 --> 00:20:33.134
Mateo is an anesthesiologist
at Hospital Alto Prado.

00:20:33.169 --> 00:20:37.976
He did his residency
at Johns Hopkins and has
worked a lot with my father.

00:20:38.012 --> 00:20:39.307
-Yes.
-He'll be helping out

00:20:39.342 --> 00:20:40.810
with your surgery tomorrow.

00:20:40.846 --> 00:20:42.107
Thank you.

00:20:42.142 --> 00:20:45.010
-I'll be right here
if you need anything.
-Thank you.

00:20:50.421 --> 00:20:52.919
This is Valentina,
one of our nurses.

00:20:52.954 --> 00:20:55.923
She'll be taking some scans
and drawing some blood,

00:20:55.958 --> 00:20:59.195
all in preparation for the
